```c++
#include <iostream>

using namespace std;

int main()
{
    int result, base = 6, exponent = 6;

    __asm__ (
        "movl   %[base], %%eax     \n"
        "movl   %[exponent], %%ecx \n"
        "movl   $1, %%ebx          \n"
        "power_loop:               \n"
        "mul    %%ecx              \n"
        "inc    %%ebx              \n"
        "cmp    $6, %%ebx          \n"
        "jle    power_loop         \n"
        "movl   %%eax, %[result]   \n"
        : [result] "=r" (result)
        : [base] "r" (base), [exponent] "r" (exponent)
        : "%eax", "%ecx", "%ebx"
    );

    cout << "6 to the power of 6 is: " << result << endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This code uses inline assembly inside a C++ program to compute the value of 6 to the power of 6 using loop. The assembly code is similar to the one we discussed earlier, but the syntax is slightly different. The values of base and exponent are loaded into eax and ecx registers respectively, and the loop is executed using the mul, inc, cmp, and jle instructions. Finally, the result is stored back in the result variable using the movl instruction. The output message is printed on the console using the cout statement.

